nish Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Francisco, Miguel, Jorge, Pedro, Ramon, Raul, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Sánchez</b>): patronymic from the personal name   Sancho  . In the US, this surname is also found among Native Americans (mainly Pueblos). Compare   De Sanchez  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Diego, Jorge, Juan, Carlos, Enrique, Miguel, Pedro, Rafael, Guillermo, Jaime.","Spanish (<b>Sáez</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sancho","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Elena, Carlos, Fernando, Jacinto, Mario, Agustin, Ana, Dulce, Emilio, Enrique, Eugenio.","Spanish and Portuguese: from <i>Sancho</i>, a popular medieval personal name, which is probably from Latin <i>Sanc(t)ius</i>, a derivative of <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy’. The personal name was borne by a 9th-century Christian martyr of Cordova."]},{"name":"Saenz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Raul, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Mario, Francisco, Pedro, Ricardo, Alfredo.","Spanish (<b>Sáenz</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sanz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Ricardo, Juan, Luis, Enrique, Jaime, Armando, Ernesto, Francisco, Manuel, Miguel.","German: from a short form, <i>Sando</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>sand</i> ‘true’.","German: habitational name from a place called Sanz in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gamboa","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Luis, Carlos, Francisco, Jesus, Mario, Miguel, Pedro, Armando, Jaime.","Basque: topographic name composed of the elements <i>gain</i> ‘peak, summit’ + <i>boa</i> ‘rounded’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elvira","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Germanic (Visigothic) origin , very common in the Middle Ages. It was not used in the English-speaking world until the 19th century, when it was made familiar as the name of the long-suffering wife of  Don Juan , both in  Mozart's  opera Don Giovanni (  1789 ) and in  Byron's  satirical epic poem Don Juan (  1819–24 ). In his comedy Blithe Spirit  Noel Coward  used it as the name of  Charles Condomine's  first wife, who returns to haunt him. It is also the name of the heroine of the Swedish film Elvira Madigan (  1967 ), directed by  Bo Widerberg , a romantic tragedy about a pair of lovers who would rather die than be separated."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Elvira Sanchez de Gamboa was born as the daughter of Andrea Aldonza Diaz de Mena. She married Pedro Lopez de Ayala about 1235, in Spain. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1326, in Spain."},"et":{"–1326":"–1326","1225–1253":"1225–1253","1246–1288":"1246–1288","1196–Female":"1196–Surnud","1326":"1326","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","1288":"1288","about 1235":"umbes 1235","1253":"1253","1196":"1196","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania","Alfaro, La Rioja, España":"Alfaro, La Rioja, Hispaania"},"fi":{